@Beau, Block 4 
People ages 18 to 29 had a majority vote of yes, and I think that it's because they are the ones either currently in college, or are currently dealing with financial struggles that student debt causes. I also think that the reason men voted yes more than women is because of college football since it's an all men's team. Another thing is that I think the reason that 60 and older have a majority of no is because whenever they were in college tuition rates were different, so they may not see that amount of struggle that some young adults go through from debt. 
I would also like to mention that my idea of getting paid by not just the college was right. The caption on the image of “The Connecticut sophomore guard Paige Bueckers, right, has a name, image and likeness deal with StockX, the online sneaker and apparel marketplace.” helps demonstrate my idea that it shouldn't just be the colleges that pay athletes. Another idea may be them getting a reduced tuition instead of being paid. Although it may seem unfair, being paid to play a sport at college may seem unfair as well, so overall I think that some form of compensation should be given and I hope that the “Name, Image and Likeness (NIL) policy” will stay active”

